DESC = 'At its core, Ianos can be described as a calculated hardliner with a psychological edge. It is designed not just to find agreements, but to actively dominate the negotiation surplus by weaponizing time, information, and stubbornness. Instead of treating negotiation as a cooperative exercise in compromise, Ianos treats it as a high-stakes game of chicken where the agent with the best poker face wins.  \r\n\r\nHere is a general, macro-level description of how the agent operates conceptually.\r\n1. The Strategic Persona: The "Uncompromising Pragmatist"\r\n\r\nIanos operates on a dual-personality timeline split into two distinct phases:  \r\n\r\n    The Iron Wall (t<0.92): For the first 92% of the negotiation, Ianos acts entirely unyielding. It continuously demands its absolute best-case outcomes, giving the opponent the impression that it is a rigid, non-conceding bot. The goal here is psychological wear-down—forcing flexible opponents to do all the heavy lifting and concession work early on.  \r\n\r\n    The Controlled Panic (t≥0.92): Only when the clock drastically runs down does Ianos show flexibility. It initiates a rapid, calculated slide down a mathematical curve to lower its demands. However, this "panic" is highly structured; it will only concede down to a pre-calculated "extraction floor" (78% of its max utility) to ensure it still walks away with the lion\'s share of the profit.  \r\n\r\n2. Active Espionage & Information Warfare\r\n\r\nUnlike simpler agents that blindly follow a preset formula, Ianos actively studies its opponent while simultaneously feeding them misinformation:  \r\n\r\n    Reading the Opponent: It tracks the history of incoming bids to analyze which negotiation issues the opponent is rigid about and which ones they are flexible on. This allows Ianos to mathematically estimate the opponent\'s hidden preferences.  \r\n\r\n    Poisoning the Well: Ianos knows that other advanced agents are trying to model its behavior too. To mess with their heads, it uses a "poisoned bidding" strategy. It takes issues that it doesn\'t care much about and constantly rotates different values for them. This injects deliberate noise into the opponent\'s data stream, blinding their learning algorithms and masking Ianos\'s true desires.  \r\n\r\n3. The "No-Bulli" Clause: Rational Pride\r\n\r\nThe defining philosophical trait of the latest version of Ianos is its refusal to be bullied.  \r\n\r\nIn automated negotiations, a common vulnerability for conceding agents is that a completely rigid opponent can simply hold a "brick wall" until the literal last second (t=0.99), forcing the other agent to accept a terrible deal just to avoid a zero-score walk-away.  \r\n\r\nIanos is mathematically protected against this trap:  \r\n\r\n    It monitors whether the opponent is giving ground. If it detects that the opponent has refused to concede over a prolonged history, it flags them as stubborn.  \r\n\r\n    Once an opponent is flagged as a bully, Ianos\'s survival instincts override its desire for a deal. It locks its floor high, completely disables its deadline safety hatches, and prepares to walk away.  \r\n\r\n    Ianos operates on the strict principle that a mutual score of zero is better than rewarding an exploitative opponent.  \r\n\r\nSummary of the Ianos Philosophy\r\n\r\nIf Ianos were a human negotiator, it would be the type to walk into a room, state an incredibly demanding price, read your facial expressions, intentionally give you confusing counter-signals, and then—if it realizes you refuse to budge an inch—happily walk out the door and let the deal collapse rather than let you get the better of it.'
